{"type":"message","id":"90772701","parentId":"bb0fcc9e","timestamp":"2026-03-24T20:37:29.988Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_l153eyruayyv_1","toolName":"process","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[LLM] response length: 2953\r\n[master 17008eb] pulse: 2026-03-24 163716\n 4 files changed, 86 insertions(+), 95 deletions(-)\n create mode 100644 memory/session/pulse_2026-03-24 163716.md\n rename mutations/{proposed => rejected}/2026-03-24 163618.mutation (100%)\n[sandbox pulse] 2026-03-24 163716 - Phase 1 is at a critical juncture - the CFI analysis is complete, revealing that CFI measures pattern information (compression) rather than causal information. The immediate next step is to empirically test whether high-CFI tokens like \"compression\" or \"causal\" actually influence research content, which would distinguish scaffolding from genuine causation.\n\nProcess exited with code 0."}],"details":{"status":"completed","sessionId":"good-ocean","exitCode":0,"aggregated":"[LLM] response length: 2953\r\n[master 17008eb] pulse: 2026-03-24 163716\n 4 files changed, 86 insertions(+), 95 deletions(-)\n create mode 100644 memory/session/pulse_2026-03-24 163716.md\n rename mutations/{proposed => rejected}/2026-03-24 163618.mutation (100%)\n[sandbox pulse] 2026-03-24 163716 - Phase 1 is at a critical juncture - the CFI analysis is complete, revealing that CFI measures pattern information (compression) rather than causal information. The immediate next step is to empirically test whether high-CFI tokens like \"compression\" or \"causal\" actually influence research content, which would distinguish scaffolding from genuine causation.\r\n","name":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\pulse.ps1"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774384649984}}
{"type":"message","id":"ef070a48","parentId":"90772701","timestamp":"2026-03-24T20:37:29.995Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_l153eyruayyv_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 163618\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: research/CONDITIONAL-CONTENT-ANALYSIS.md (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine the best next action.\r\n\r\nLooking at the goals:\r\n- Phase 0 COMPLETE\r\n- Phase 1 IN PROGRESS: Compression primitives - CFI analysis complete, next is conditional content analysis\r\n- The \"🔥 CORE BREAKTHROUGH: CFI ≠ Causal Discovery\" was documented\r\n\r\nThe pending experiment is:\r\n**Conditional Content Analysis** (highest priority)\r\n- For moderate-frequency tokens (freq=60-80%), split pulse pairs into T-present and T-absent groups\r\n- Question: does research content of next-pulse differ between groups?\r\n- This distinguishes Pattern Information from Causal Information empirically\r\n\r\nLooking at the key insights:\r\n1. \"Phase 1\" (freq=136, CFI=0.96) is true research trajectory - causal but not constant\r\n2. CFI ≥ 0.5 AND freq ∈ [3, 120) is the three-dimensional filter\r\n3. The current experiment result shows: Strategy A (freq-only) has precision=0.4254 but the best F1=0.2527\r\n\r\nThe core question: Is the next action to run the conditional content analysis experiment, or to document/synthesize something?\r\n\r\nGiven the \"No mutations applied this cycle\" note, I should take an action that advances the goals.\r\n\r\nThe conditional content analysis is the highest priority pending experiment. But it's complex - it requires:\r\n1. Identifying moderate-frequency tokens (freq=60-80%)\r\n2. Splitting pulse pairs into T-present and T-absent groups\r\n3. Comparing research content of next-pulse between groups\r\n\r\nLet me think about what concrete action I can take. The analysis would require:\r\n- Running code to identify tokens in the 60-80% frequency range\r\n- Then analyzing the content differences\r\n\r\nActually, looking at the data:\r\n- \"compression\" has freq=199, CFI=0.995 (too high - constant)\r\n\r\n\r\n- \"causal\" has freq=162, CFI=0.981 (too high)\r\n- \"phase\" has freq=187, CFI=0.946 (too high)\r\n\r\nTokens with freq in 60-80% range (120-160 out of 200) would be:\r\n- \"causal\" at freq=162, CFI=0.981 is just outside\r\n- Need to find tokens with freq between 120-160\r\n\r\nI'll focus on identifying these specific tokens. The goal is to find moderate-frequency tokens that can help distinguish between Pattern and Causal Information. By carefully selecting tokens in the 60-80% frequency range, I can design a targeted experiment to test these theoretical insights.\r\n\r\nThe next step is creating a precise token selection strategy that allows me to split pulse pairs and analyze content differences systematically.\r\n\r\nI'm developing a methodical approach to extract and validate tokens for deeper linguistic investigation.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe highest priority pending experiment is **Conditional Content Analysis**, which tests whether high-CFI tokens are genuinely causal or merely scaffolding. This requires first identifying which tokens have moderate frequency (60-80% = 120-160 out of 200 pulses), since constant tokens (freq=200) are known to be inert.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate a script to extract moderate-frequency tokens from the corpus, then run the conditional content analysis to empirically distinguish Pattern Information from Causal Information. This advances Phase 1 from analysis to validation.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # Conditional Content Analysis\r\n# Tests: does presence of token T predict different next-pulse content?\r\n# Distinguishes Pattern Information (CFI) from Causal Information (actual content changes)\r\n\r\n# Candidates: tokens with freq 60-80% (120-160 / 200 pulses)\r\n# Avoids constant tokens (freq=200) and rare tokens (freq<20)\r\n\r\nimport os\r\nimport re\r\nfrom collections import defaultdict\r\nfrom pathlib import Path\r\n\r\nCORPUS_DIR = Path(\"pulses\")\r\nPULSE_FILES = sorted(CORPUS_DIR.glob(\"pulse_*.md\"))\r\n\r\n# Parse all pulses\r\ndef extract_text(filepath):\r\n    with open(filepath) as f:\r\n        content = f.read()\r\n    # Strip metadata header if present\r\n    if \"### \" in content:\r\n        return content.split(\"### \", 1)[1]\r\n    return content\r\n\r\npulses = {}\r\nfor pf in PULSE_FILES:\r\n    pulses[pf.name] = extract_text(pf)\r\n\r\n# Load precomputed token stats\r\ntoken_stats = {}\r\nstats_file = Path(\"research/token_stats.csv\")\r\nif stats_file.exists():\r\n    with open(stats_file) as f:\r\n        for line in f:\r\n            parts = line.strip().split(\",\")\r\n            if len(parts) >= 2:\r\n                token, freq = parts[0], int(parts[1])\r\n                token_stats[token] = {\"freq\": freq}\r\n\r\n# Find moderate-frequency tokens (120-160 range)\r\nmoderate_tokens = [t for t, s in token_stats.items() \r\n                   if 120 <= s.get(\"freq\", 0) <= 160]\r\nmoderate_tokens.sort(key=lambda t: token_stats[t][\"freq\"], reverse=True)\r\n\r\nprint(f\"Tokens in 60-80% freq range (120-160): {len(moderate_tokens)}\")\r\nfor t in moderate_tokens[:15]:\r\n    print(f\"  {t}: freq={token_stats[t]['freq']}\")\r\nprint()\r\n\r\n# For each moderate token, analyze next-pulse content\r\ndef jaccard_similarity(set1, set2):\r\n    if not set1 or not set2:\r\n        return 0.0\r\n    intersection = len(set1 & set2)\r\n    union = len(set1 | set2)\r\n    return intersection / union if union > 0 else 0.0\r\n\r\ndef tokenize(text):\r\n    return set(re.findall(r'\\b\\w{4,\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 16:36:39\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774384649988}}
